It’s been thirteen months since my spinal fusion. Thirteen months of trying things I feared would be impossible only to find that they were, in fact, very possible. Today felt like the biggest one yet. I was supposed to fly out this morning early after the auction last night. But after the snow started falling yesterday I pushed to an evening flight. I rented skis, went through the motions of putting on my boots and skis all the while expecting my first run to be painful-  or worse - a validation of my fear I would never be able to ski again. It was the opposite. After the first two runs in the driving snow I forgot about my back. I stopped worrying about pain and focused on making it down the mountain. I did blues and then blacks and then a double black. And I remembered again that facing fears is what makes us stronger, more confident and ultimately allows us to live the life we want. I hope you read this and it encourages you to try something you thought you couldn’t do or makes you go after something you feared you would never be able to do again. Who knows? It could be the opposite 🎿❄️⛷🙏🏻

Part of Mariana’s legacy will be she left behind friends who are now family, bonded in memory and love for a woman who can never be replaced, and will never be forgotten. Love you M. 🤍🕊🤍

Finding Your Fire
From being a National Correspondent for CNN, to contributing to CBS Sunday Morning and hosting The Atelier with Alina Cho at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Alina Cho’s expansive career in journalism has made her a role model for many. In this interview, we talk about how Alina fell in love with storytelling through learning on the job, her experiences traveling to North Korea for correspondence, and how she juggles all of her current and upcoming projects. Be sure to tune in to this episode where we discuss:
The importance of having hands-on experience when beginning your career
How Alina’s work has made her an inspiration for younger generations
Having tenacity, and the power that comes with overcoming the fear of being told no
Her experiences covering a wide variety of stories – from national correspondence in North Korea and reporting on-location in Louisiana during Hurricane Katrina, to reintroducing fashion reporting to CNN with her series Fashion: Backstage Pass
How being your own best advocate is integral to success

To rid yourself of imposter syndrome, remember one key fact: People are rarely thinking about you at all. Confidence comes when you realize it doesn't matter what anyone else thinks about you. Your foolproof "I got this.” 
S--STOP counting yourself out.
L--LISTEN to what someone is saying, not what you think they are saying.
A--ACCEPT that no one gives you a gold star except you.
M--MAKE your point and don't back down.

Triple black diamond was so nice, we skied it twice🎿🎿 Four days after the car accident, when I was flat on my back in the hospital bed with a fractured spine, my doctor sat down to tell me what I could expect after the accident. The only question I asked was “will I be able to do everything I could do before the accident”? He hesitated “not everything, but pretty close”. I made up my mind that minute  I wouldn’t do everything I had done before the accident, I would do more. Recovery was long and painful, but I committed to every part of it and never looked back. Today Chris and I skied a triple black diamond twice (who even knew there was such a thing?). You can choose to stay in your comfort zone or push yourself and reap the rewards on the other side. The next time you doubt yourself, remember this story and go for it. You are the catalyst for every change you want in your life 🎿🙌🏻🎿 #claimyourconfidence #mindset #poweryourpositivity

I’m backstage waiting to go onstage for an auction this eve. You’ve been asking for work travel hacks, so while I wait I thought I’d share my fail-proof list for making work travel enjoyable:
-Take the first flight out so you know the plane is at the airport - no delays, no stress (as long as you wake up).
-Pack a carry on. I’m kidding. Pack whatever makes you feel like you have options. I always throw in plenty of extra outfits bc you never know what is going to happen. I packed a 60pd suitcase for a four day trip once. Ask my husband if you don’t believe me. 
-Stay with friends instead of a hotel so you can catch up during down times. 
-Don’t sit in your hotel room when you aren’t working. -Explore, try a restaurant, take a walk/run, use social media to find people you once knew and reconnect or get recommendations. Travel is fun if you make it an adventure.

If you knew me before our car accident, you knew how much I loved to run. As long as I can remember, running has been my mood lifter, my mode of exploration and the time when I have my best ideas. Both of my books were written after a series of long runs -  I would run straight to my computer to write down everything before I lost it. On Halloween 2021 that all came to a full stop when our car was hit head on fracturing my lower back. Four days later I went in for a spinal fusion to repair it. As I attempted to stand up after the surgery, with multiple ribs broken in the front and a newly fused spine, I almost blacked out from the pain. Even in those early days, I prayed that I would be able to run again. My memories of those early days in PT can only be described as mind over body. Spirit over ability. I leaned on my family and friends both mentally for encouragement and physically because I couldn’t stand for long periods of time. But each day the walks got a little longer. I moved further and further away from our apartment. As the weeks turned to months, I slowly started to pick up my feet and run again. 100 feet, 200 feet, 500 feet, my first mile. I’m truth, it doesn’t feel the same and never will. But every day I lace up my shoes and choose to go for the run I am reminded of the power of moving. Moving forward, moving through the difficult times. Simply moving. Life is full of the good, but it’s also full of times that are far from good. We know the highs because we know the lows in life. Keep moving. Every day is a new day 🌄 ❤️ #motivationmonday #motivation

The past eighteen months have been filled with transitions and changes that I could never have foreseen. There have been the highest highs and the lowest lows, and as usual that brings me back to the same place. Fingers itching to type, a story waiting to be told, another book ready to be written.
I dropped off my kids yesterday and headed to Round Top, Tx, far far away from the busy pace of my day to day life. I sat poolside as the sun set - and the temperature dropped from the 100s to 90s - and started writing. I forget how quickly the stories come when they are ready.
Between last night and this morning I wrote the first chapter of the book. If you've been following me for a bit you already know that the story of my life is told at warp speed. It makes sense that writing a book should be done in exactly the same way, even if the place where I am writing moves at the pace of a hot Texas summer day. 
Headed home today, but will never forget how this book started in such a special way. 💙💙💙

I woke up this morning with my 2024 resolutions set. I was going to start the morning running the 3.5 mile lake loop; one of my favorites runs when I’m home. As I set off I was already thinking about the fork in the road that leads to the five mile loop. I haven’t run five miles since my spinal surgery two years ago - crazy because I ran at least five miles a day for twenty years leading up to the accident. Truthfully I think I was scared to try in case my back couldn’t handle it. When I came to the fork in the road I willed myself to keep going straight instead of taking a right to the smaller loop. And guess what? I ran five miles like I had never missed a day. I was on such a high I called my sister, who has been trying to get me to do a polar plunge for years, and met her to jump in a frigid pool. And so, I changed my 2024 resolution. In 2024 I will try things I think I can’t do, things that scare me, things that make me want to run away. I may fail. I may fail in a big way. But it’s not going to stop me from trying. If you haven’t figured out your New Year’s resolution, join me. 2024 is the year we find the fun in failure. I think we are all going to realize how much more capable we are than we ever thought possible. Here we come 2024 💃🏻💃🏻💃🏻 #2024 #2024resolutions #havegavelwilltravel
